metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #268
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #22
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: DrumMachine: GD-X 001 #11
metadata.description:
A drum machine design which is controlled by clickable step sequencer with many effect units. Start the loop and enable steps for sound!

//

START/STOP(Click): Starts and stops the 16-step loop, markers become black when it is on the loop; orange when it is off the loop.

4x 16 GRİD(Click): Enables the step of Kick/Snare/Hi-hat/Clap part and marks, steps will be played on the loop.

BPM: Fader controls the speed of the loop

GRAİNS: Fader controls granular delay effect

ECHO: Fader controls the echo effect

OVERDRİVE: Fader controls the overdrive effect

*** Token instruments for Metaverse and browser usage.

metadata.name: fields, wireframes #106
metadata.description:
The second part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: Utopian Skyline #67
metadata.description:
Continuing the exploration of linear composition in the previous work, this work shows the utopian urban structure in an abstract form by using diagonal and non-uniform lines. To make this artwork more scattered and visually dynamic, just like musical notes that have to be interrupted somewhere, the lines are scattered and discontinuous using an animation algorithm. To see the artwork in detail, open it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: paintflow #198
metadata.description:
For this project, I wanted to try out Ty Vek's SVG technique for creating gen art. I used some basic SVG filters to achieve the paint brush effect, then just added some simple line and curve patterns. The result is quite nice and organic feeling! There are only 2 colors: red and black - I felt it was important to focus on the shapes and lines rather than the colors. The number of curves varies from 2 to 4, and each can be filled above or below. That's the gist of it! I hope you get some pretty pieces.

You can save the generated SVG by pressing the 's' key, and you can save a PNG version by pressing the 'p' key.

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: Unfolded #318
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Artifact #165
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.
